    <h1>MGB 301: Test 2 Study Guide (Spring 2026)</h1>

    <!-- COLUMN 1: CHAPTER 9 -->
    <section>
        <h2>CH 9: GROUP BEHAVIOR</h2>
        <p><span class="bold">Group:</span> 2+ individuals, interacting & interdependent, to achieve objectives.</p>
        <p><span class="bold">Team:</span> Subset of groups; shared leadership, collective accountability, specific purpose.</p>
        
        <h3>5-Stage Model</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><span class="bold">Forming:</span> Uncertainty about purpose/leadership.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Storming:</span> Intragroup conflict; resist constraints.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Norming:</span> Cohesiveness, identity, standard behavior.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Performing:</span> Fully functional, focused on task.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Adjourning:</span> Wrap-up (temporary groups).</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Group Properties</h3>
        <p><span class="bold">Roles:</span> Expected behavior patterns.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><span class="italic">Perception:</span> Our view of how to act.</li>
            <li><span class="italic">Expectations:</span> Others' view of how we should act.</li>
            <li><span class="italic">Psych Contract:</span> Unwritten agreement (employer/ee).</li>
            <li><span class="italic">Conflict:</span> Divergent role expectations.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><span class="bold">Norms:</span> Acceptable standards of behavior.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><span class="italic">Hawthorne:</span> Social identity/norms > money/conditions.</li>
            <li><span class="italic">Conformity:</span> Adjusting behavior to align with group (Asch Study).</li>
        </ul>
        <p><span class="bold">Status:</span> Socially defined position. High status = more freedom to deviate from norms.</p>
        <p><span class="bold">Size:</span> <span class="italic">Social Loafing</span> (expending less effort when working collectively). Ringelmann’s Rope Pull. Prevention: individual accountability.</p>
        <p><span class="bold">Cohesiveness:</span> Attraction to each other. 
            <br>- High Coh + High Perf Norms = <span class="bold">High Prod.</span>
            <br>- High Coh + Low Perf Norms = <span class="bold">Low Prod.</span>
        </p>

        <h3>Decision Making</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><span class="bold">Groupthink:</span> Norm for consensus overrides appraisal of alternatives.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Groupshift:</span> Polarized views (more extreme/risky).</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Brainstorming:</span> Idea generation, no criticism.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">NGT:</span> Nominal Group Technique. Silent idea gen -> Round robin -> Discussion -> Independent Ranking.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- COLUMN 2: CHAPTER 10 & 11 -->
    <section>
        <h2>CH 10: WORK TEAMS</h2>
        <p><span class="bold">Synergy:</span> Individual efforts result in performance > sum of inputs. Groups = Neutral/Neg synergy; Teams = Pos synergy.</p>
        
        <h3>Types of Teams</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><span class="bold">Problem-Solving:</span> 5-12 people, same dept, improve quality/efficiency.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Self-Managed:</span> 10-15 people, take on supervisor roles (scheduling, planning).</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Cross-Functional:</span> Same level, different work areas (Task forces, committees).</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Virtual:</span> Computer-linked, geographically dispersed.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Effectiveness Model</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><span class="bold">Context:</span> Resources, Leadership/Structure, Trust, Performance/Rewards.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Composition:</span> Ability, Personality (Conscientiousness), Roles, Diversity, Size (5-9 ideal), Flexibility.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Work Design:</span> Autonomy, Skill Variety, Task Identity, Task Significance.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Process:</span> Common Purpose, Specific Goals, Efficacy, Conflict levels, Reduced Loafing.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>CH 11: COMMUNICATION</h2>
        <p><span class="bold">Process:</span> Sender (Encodes) -> Message -> Channel -> Receiver (Decodes) -> Feedback. (Noise interferes).</p>
        
        <h3>Direction & Networks</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><span class="bold">Down:</span> Goals, instructions.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Up:</span> Feedback, progress, problems.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Lateral:</span> Coordination between peers.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><span class="bold">Networks:</span>
            <br>1. <span class="bold">Chain:</span> Follows formal chain of command.
            <br>2. <span class="bold">Wheel:</span> Central leader acts as conduit.
            <br>3. <span class="bold">All-Channel:</span> Active participation, fast, high satisfaction.
        </p>
        <p><span class="bold">Grapevine:</span> Informal, 75% accuracy, used when info is important, ambiguous, or causes anxiety.</p>
        <p><span class="bold">Richness:</span> Ability to handle multiple cues, fast feedback, personal. 
            <br>- <span class="bold">High:</span> Face-to-face. 
            <br>- <span class="bold">Low:</span> Formal reports, memos.
        </p>
        <p><span class="bold">Barriers:</span> Filtering, Selective Perception, Information Overload, Emotions, Language, Communication Apprehension (Anxiety).</p>
    </section>

    <!-- COLUMN 3: CHAPTER 12 (Leadership Part 1) -->
    <section>
        <h2>CH 12: LEADERSHIP</h2>
        <p><span class="bold">Lead vs Mgmt:</span> Leaders challenge status quo/create vision; Managers bring order/consistency through plans.</p>
        
        <h3>Trait & Behavioral</h3>
        <p><span class="bold">Trait Theory:</span> Leaders are born. Key: Extraversion (strongest), Conscientiousness, Openness, EI.</p>
        <p><span class="bold">Behavioral:</span> Leaders are trained.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><span class="bold">Ohio State:</span> <span class="italic">Initiating Structure</span> (define roles/goals) vs <span class="italic">Consideration</span> (trust/respect).</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Michigan:</span> <span class="italic">Employee-Oriented</span> vs <span class="italic">Production-Oriented</span>.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Managerial Grid:</span> (Concern for People vs Production). <span class="highlight">9,9 (Team Mgmt)</span> is ideal.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Contingency Theories</h3>
        <p><span class="bold">Fiedler Model:</span> Leader style is fixed (LPC scale: High = Relation; Low = Task). Effectiveness depends on <span class="italic">Situation Control</span>:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>1. Leader-member relations.</li>
            <li>2. Task structure.</li>
            <li>3. Position power.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Task-Oriented:</span> Best in very favorable or very unfavorable situations.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Relation-Oriented:</span> Best in moderate situations.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><span class="bold">Cognitive Resource:</span> Stress affects leadership. High stress -> Experience > Intelligence. Low stress -> Intelligence > Experience.</p>
        <p><span class="bold">Path-Goal Theory (House):</span> Leader job is to clarify paths to goals and remove roadblocks. Styles:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><span class="italic">Directive:</span> Guidance (best if task is ambiguous).</li>
            <li><span class="italic">Supportive:</span> Concern for needs (best if task is stressful).</li>
            <li><span class="italic">Participative:</span> Consults followers.</li>
            <li><span class="italic">Achievement:</span> Sets high goals.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><span class="bold">LMX Theory:</span> Leaders create In-Groups (higher ratings, lower turnover) and Out-Groups.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- COLUMN 4: CHAPTER 12 & 14 -->
    <section>
        <h2>CH 12 (CONT.) & CH 14</h2>
        
        <h3>Charismatic Leadership</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><span class="bold">Charisma:</span> Vision, personal risk, sensitivity to followers, unconventional behavior.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Dark Side:</span> Personal goals override org goals; narcissism.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Full Range of Leadership</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><span class="bold">Transactional:</span> Laissez-Faire (avoid), Management by Exception (Passive/Active), Contingent Reward (exchange).</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Transformational:</span> 4 I’s: 1. <span class="italic">Idealized Influence</span> (Pride/Trust), 2. <span class="italic">Inspirational Motivation</span> (Expectations), 3. <span class="italic">Intellectual Stimulation</span> (Rationality), 4. <span class="italic">Individualized Consideration</span> (Personal attention).</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>CH 14: CONFLICT & NEGOTIATION</h2>
        <p><span class="bold">Conflict Views:</span>
            <br>- <span class="bold">Traditional:</span> Bad, avoid.
            <br>- <span class="bold">Interactionist:</span> Positive force, necessary for performance.
            <br>- <span class="bold">Resolution-Focused:</span> Manage it productively.
        </p>
        <h3>Types of Conflict</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><span class="bold">Task:</span> Goals/Content (Functional if low/mod).</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Relationship:</span> Interpersonal (Always Dysfunctional).</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Process:</span> How work gets done (Functional if low).</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Negotiation (Bargaining)</h3>
        <p><span class="bold">Distributive:</span> Win-Lose, fixed pie, opposed interests, low info sharing.</p>
        <p><span class="bold">Integrative:</span> Win-Win, expand the pie, congruent interests, high info sharing. (Best for long-term relations).</p>
        
        <h3>Key Terms</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><span class="bold">BATNA:</span> Best Alternative To a Negotiated Agreement. (Your power source).</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Target Point:</span> What you want to achieve.</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Resistance Point:</span> Lowest acceptable outcome (Bottom line).</li>
            <li><span class="bold">Bargaining Zone:</span> Space between resistance points.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Creating Value</h3>
        <p>Build trust, share info, trade off issues (Logrolling), make multiple offers simultaneously, package deals.</p>
    </section>
